IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: *Maryland State Police Frederick Barrack* Vehicle: Red Unmarked Ford Explorer B-18 Body Camera Equipped and Functioning: Yes In-car Camera Equipped and Functioning: Yes OFFICERS ON SCENE: TFC Berger, Cpl Mattingly, FCSO Yakovich Case Number: 23-MSP-009475 Date: 03/15/2023 Time: 2019 hours Location: W/B I-70 @ MM 56 ATTACHMENTS: MSP Form 63 MSP Form 64 MSP Form 67 (2) Statement of Charges Statement of PC METERS Warning VICTIM / COMPLAINANT: Victim#1: State of Maryland 110 Airport Drive East Frederick, Maryland 21701 301-600-4150 Complainant #1: Trooper Berger #7011 Maryland State Police Frederick Barrack 110 Airport Drive East Frederick, Maryland 21701 301-600-4150 WITNESS: FCSO DFC Yakovich MSP Cpl Mattingly SUSPECT / SEATING LOCATION: Suspect #1 (Driver) Kyle Anthoney Keller (W/M DOB: 12/17/1993) 9 West Clement St, Cumberland, MD 21502 240-609-9719 Suspect #2 (Front Seat Passenger) John David Diehl (W/M DOB: 12/28/1981) 2336 Beaver Run Rd, Burlington, WV 26710 NARRATIVE: Vehicle in Motion: On March 15, 2023 at 2015 hours, I, TFC Berger #7011, was stationary in the I-70 crossover at Linganore Road, observing traffic on westbound I-70 for violations. At approximately 2017 hours, I observed a black Ford Ecosport bearing WV registration 46R769, traveling in lane three. The Ford appeared to be following the vehicle in front of it too closely, it was approximately one and a half car lengths away from the vehicle in front of it at highway speeds of 65 MPH. I also observed as the Ford passed me that the driver was putting a fresh cigarette in his mouth. I also observed the driver and front seat passenger staring at me as they passed. I exited the crossover and conducted a traffic stop on the Ford on the right shoulder of westbound I-70 at MM 56. Personal Contact: I contacted the vehicle occupants via the passenger side window. I introduced myself, explained the reason for the stop, and advised both occupants that they were being audibly and visually recorded. I then requested the drivers license and vehicle registration. While the driver retrieved these documents, I asked about their travel today. The passenger advised that they were coming back from car shopping. I inquired where they had been car shopping and he seemed hesitant to answer that question. He stated he was not exactly sure. The driver then handed me his Maryland Drivers License which identified him as Kyle Anthoney Keller (W/M DOB: 12/17/1993). As Keller surrendered his license, I observed his hands to be shaking. I had to again ask for the vehicle registration. I also asked the passenger for his ID, which he surrendered. He was identified as John David Diehl (W/M DOB: 12/28/1981). While the registration was being looked for, I again posed the question of where exactly they had been car shopping at, Diehl again seemed hesitant, all he was able to say is that it was this side of Baltimore and we were just following the GPS. Reasonable Articulable Suspicion: Based on the following reasons observed in the vehicle in motion and personal contact phase, I believed there to be criminal activity afoot: traveling as far away from my patrol vehicle as possible, fresh cigarette, odor masking materials in the vehicle (black ice air freshener hanging from mirror), occupants staring at patrol vehicle as they pass it, shaking hands, avoiding eye contact, vague answers regarding travel, prior CDS arrests. Due to these criminal indicators, I requested the assistance of a CDS detection K9. Probable Cause: While I was awaiting license and wanted checks from the Frederick Barrack PCO, FCSO DFC Yakovich responded to the scene with his K9 partner Eik. Yakovich agreed to conduct a K9 scan of the vehicle. At that time, myself and Cpl Mattingly removed Keller and Diehl from the vehicle and brought them to the rear of my patrol vehicle so the scan could safely be conducted. I explained to them that due to things I had observed before and during the stop, DFC Yakovich was going to be conducting a K9 scan. I asked if there was anything that we needed to be made aware of. Keller then said I have something on me. I immediately read Keller and Diehl their Miranda rights, which they both acknowledged they understood. I then pulled Keller aside and asked what he had. He informed me that there were approximately 5-10 capsules of Fentanyl on his person. At this time, the K9 positively alerted to the odor of CDS in the vehicle. I then asked Keller what was in the vehicle. He informed me that there were 500 capsules of Fentanyl in the vehicle in a black backpack. Search of Vehicle and/or Occupants: Due to the positive K9 scan, the vehicle was searched, in a black backpack on the center back seat of the Ford, were numerous clear baggies containing gel capsules suspected of containing CDS Schedule II Fentanyl. There were also baggies containing CDS Schedule II Crack Cocaine. On the floorboards behind the passenger seat was a small black pouch containing various CDS paraphernalia. On Kellers person was a clear vile containing 4 capsules of CDS Schedule II Fentanyl. Due to lose Fentanyl powder, the black pouch and several of the baggies of Fentanyl were unable to be analyzed. However, the total weight of the contraband was 231.1 grams of Fentanyl, and 29.3 grams of Crack Cocaine. Arrest: Keller claimed ownership of all CDS, he was arrested and transported to the MSP Frederick Barrack while the evidence was processed. He was then transported to FCADC. Timeline Summary: *Time of Stop - 2019 *K9 Requested - 2023 *K9 On Scene 2031 *Miranda 2032 *Positive Alert - 2035 *Contraband located - 2041 *Time of Arrest 2107 CHARGES: *1_1111* CR 5-601(a)(1): CDS Possess/ Not Cannabis (2 counts) *1_1119* CR 5-602: CDS Possess/ Intent to Distribute/ Narc (2 counts) *1_0881* CR 5-612: CDS Possess/ Large Amount/ Fentanyl All criminal indicators and CDS were identified using my training, knowledge, experience, and prior drug arrests, as a Maryland State Trooper. All the above events occurred in Frederick County, Maryland. Case Status: Closed

On May 17, 2023, I, TFC Berger #7011, served Keller with his circuit court summons at FCADC. Keller signed the document voluntarily. I also received drug results which confirmed the presence of CDS Fentanyl and CDS Cocaine in the seized contraband. There were also amounts of CDS Heroin and CDS Methamphetamine. The results are attached. All events occurred in Frederick County, MD.
